Project on Ensembled Machine Learing Techniques¶

Deadline August 31, 2021

Selling personal loans¶

The given project1.xlsx file contains data on 5000 customers of a bank with demographic information such as age, income, etc., thier relationship with the bank like mortgage, securities account, etc., and the response to the last personal loan campaign. Among these 5000 customers, only 480 accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign. The number of customers who are also borrowers is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans.

Column Understanding¶

Nominal Variables¶

Variables used to name, lable or catagorize particular attribute where there is no intrinsic ordering. Examples: Phone Number, National Identification Number, Postal Code

In the Bank Customer Data, the nominal variables are:

  1. ID -
  2. ZIP Code - Address code of customer

Ordinal Variables¶

Are measurement variable that takes values with an order or rank, with or without numerical values.

In the Bank Customer Data, the ordinal categorical variables are:

  1. Family - No of family for the customer
  2. Education - level of education of customer

Interval Variables¶

Interval variables are measured along a scale, with each point placed at an equal distance from one another.

The interval variables are:

  1. Age - age of customer
  2. Experience - years of experience
  3. Income - annual income in thousands
  4. CCAvg - avg credit card spending
  5. Mortage - value of the house mortage

Catagorical Variables¶

The binary category have five variables as below:

The binary catagorical variables are:

  1. Personal Loan - if customer took last loan offer
  2. Securities Account - weather customer have a securities account
  3. CD Account - if customer have a certificate of deposit account
  4. Online - if customer use internet banking
  5. Credit Card - if customer use a credit card issued

Negative Value Replacement¶

We can replace each negative 'Experience' value with the median of possitive 'Experience' associated with the particular 'Age' and 'Education' value.

In [9]:
df_Possitive_Experience = bank_customers[bank_customers['Experience'] > 0]
df_Negative_Experience =  bank_customers[bank_customers['Experience'] < 0]
df_Negative_Experience_List = df_Negative_Experience['ID'].tolist()

for id in df_Negative_Experience_List:
    age_values = bank_customers.loc[np.where(bank_customers['ID']==id)]["Age"].tolist()[0]
    education_values = bank_customers.loc[np.where(bank_customers['ID']==id)]["Education"].tolist()[0]
    possitive_Experience_Filtered = df_Possitive_Experience[(df_Possitive_Experience['Age'] == age_values) & 
                                                (df_Possitive_Experience['Education'] == education_values)]
    if possitive_Experience_Filtered.empty :
        negative_Experience_Filtered = df_Negative_Experience[(df_Negative_Experience['Age'] == age_values) & 
                                                (df_Negative_Experience['Education'] == education_values)]
        exp = round(negative_Experience_Filtered['Experience'].median())
    else:
        exp = round(possitive_Experience_Filtered['Experience'].median())
    bank_customers.loc[bank_customers.loc[np.where(bank_customers['ID']==id)].index, 'Experience'] = abs(exp)

Finding¶

There is an outlier on the ZIP Code and relatively higher varaince on ID and ZIP Code

  1. Drop ID - it is an ordinal variable with numerical value showing no inherent rank or order, just used to index customer data
  2. ZIP Code - it is also an ordinal variable with numerical value where the value is actualy catagorical (a specific ZIP Code indicating customers from the same area)
    • It does not show rank or order (just number given to an area)
    • It has a very high standard deviation and high value of range not qualifying to be used as catagory

Task 5¶

Use a different classification models to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

Insert a new cell below this cell to put your answer

In [25]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn import metrics
from sklearn import model_selection
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.naive_bayes import GaussianNB
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
In [26]:
models = []
models.append(('GNB', GaussianNB()))
models.append(('SVC', SVC(probability=True, kernel='linear')))
models.append(('LR ', LogisticRegression()))
models.append(('KNN', KNeighborsClassifier()))
models.append(('DTC', DecisionTreeClassifier()))

# Model comparision 
results = []
names = []
scoring = 'accuracy'
for name, model in models:
    k_fold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=20, random_state=10,shuffle=True)
    cv_results = model_selection.cross_val_score(model, X_minmax, y, cv=k_fold, scoring=scoring)
    results.append(cv_results)
    names.append(name)
    print(name, cv_results.mean())

# boxplot algorithm comparison
fig = plt.figure()
fig.suptitle('Algorithm Comparison')
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
plt.boxplot(results)
ax.set_xticklabels(names)
plt.show()

from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostClassifier


dt_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion = "entropy", random_state = 10,
                                            max_depth=5, min_samples_leaf=5)
dt_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_predict_no_adaboost = dt_clf.predict(X_test)
print ("Decision Tree Classifier Accuracy is:  ", accuracy_score(y_test,y_predict_no_adaboost)*100)

ab_clf = AdaBoostClassifier(base_estimator= dt_clf,n_estimators=100,learning_rate=.01, random_state=10)
ab_clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

y_predict_adaboost = ab_clf.predict(X_test)
print ("AdaBoost on Decision Tree Accuracy is: ", accuracy_score(y_test,y_predict_adaboost)*100)

Decision Tree Classifier Accuracy is:   98.66666666666667

AdaBoost on Decision Tree Accuracy is:  99.06666666666666

With Hyper Parameter Tuning¶

In [30]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

abc = AdaBoostClassifier(base_estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion = "entropy", random_state = 10))

parameters = {'base_estimator__max_depth':[i for i in range(1,10,2)],
              'base_estimator__min_samples_leaf':[5,10],
              'n_estimators':[50,100,250],
              'learning_rate':[0.001,0.01,0.1],
              'random_state':[10]}

gscv = GridSearchCV(abc, parameters,verbose=3,scoring='f1',n_jobs=-1)
gscv.fit(X_train,y_train)
y_predict_abc = gscv.predict(X_test)
print ("AdaBoost on Decision Tree Accuracy is: ", accuracy_score(y_test,y_predict_abc)*100)

Fitting 5 folds for each of 90 candidates, totalling 450 fits

AdaBoost on Decision Tree Accuracy is:  99.06666666666666
